    • Alok Jagawat The Mahenjo daro as mentioned by you is close to Kalyuga period. The ratios used in measurements in Mohenjo daro are mentioned in Mayamattam. These ratios of length and breadth are important part of Sthpathya because it defines the Aya units which is required for yonis. The college in Mohenjo-daro follows a ratio of 3:1. The granary follows a ratio of 4:3. A ratio of 5:4 is present in major sites at Dholavira and at assembly hall of Mahoenjo daro.
      Mayamattam mentions these ratios in the chapter gramvinyas:
      |
      ||||

      According to ancient treatises a kings abode, cities and roads should follow 108 angula praman which can be seen in all mature sites of Indus valley. Moreover, the brick ratio in Harappan sites is 1:2:4 which cannot be a mere coincidence.
      Dholaviras Ratios in construction are in exact match with what is mentioned in Brihat Sahinta of Vrhamihira . A perfect mathematical match with the ancient granthas cannot be termed as coincidence. Mr.Mohan Pant and Mr.Shuji Funo in their research papers for Mahonejo Daro and Kathmandu valley have mentioned the grid and modular measures. These measures are a match with Rajju as mentioned in arthaastra of kautilya.
